\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The basic structure\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 SH0ES is a 
\f0\b three-rung distance ladder
\f1\b0  with multi-anchor calibration:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Rung 1 (anchors)
\f1\b0 : NGC 4258 maser + LMC DEBs + MW Gaia parallaxes 
\f0\b Rung 2 (calibrators)
\f1\b0 : Cepheids in the anchors AND in SN Ia host galaxies 
\f0\b Rung 3 (Hubble flow)
\f1\b0 : SN Ia in the calibrator hosts AND in the Hubble flow\
The genius of the SH0ES design \'97 and the reason it has dominated H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  measurement for over a decade \'97 is that 
\f0\b every rung is observed with the same instrument and the same filters
\f1\b0 . All Cepheids in all rung-1 anchors and all rung-2 SN Ia hosts are observed with HST WFC3 in F555W, F814W, and F160W. All SN Ia photometry is on uniform photometric systems. This eliminates the cross-instrument zero-point errors that historically dominated distance-ladder work.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 The key quantities that get fit simultaneously\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 In the language of R22, the SH0ES global fit determines:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f0\b Cepheid period\'96luminosity\'96metallicity (PLZ) relation
\f1\b0 : $M_\{H,W\} = M_\{H,W\}^1 + b_W \\log P + Z_W [\\text\{O/H\}]$ where $M_\{H,W\}$ is the Wesenheit magnitude (an extinction-free combination of F555W, F814W, F160W magnitudes that's robust to interstellar reddening).\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f0\b PLZ zero point
\f1\b0  $M_\{H,W\}^1$, simultaneously constrained by the anchor distances.\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f0\b distance moduli
\f1\b0  $\\mu_i$ to all 42 SN Ia host galaxies via their Cepheids.\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f0\b fiducial SN Ia absolute magnitude
\f1\b0  $M_B^0$.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f1\b0  itself, via the zero point of the SN Ia Hubble diagram in the redshift range 0.0233 < z < 0.15.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f0\b cosmic deceleration parameter
\f1\b0  $q_0$ (in the joint fit version).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 All of this is one global maximum-likelihood fit with ~3000+ Cepheids, 42 calibrator SN Ia, ~277 Hubble-flow SN Ia, and the three anchor distance measurements as constraints. The total parameter space is large but the structure is linear once you've Wesenheit-corrected the photometry.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

